                "## Plotting a Position — The Three-Bearing Fix",
                "Now that you can convert bearings, the next step is to **fix the ship's position on the chart**. The gold standard of coastal position fixing is the **three-bearing visual fix** — three simultaneous compass bearings of three charted objects, converted to true, and plotted on the chart.",
                "**Why three?** A single bearing only tells you that you are somewhere along a line. Two bearings give a theoretical point, but if there is any error in one bearing, you would not know. Three bearings create three position lines — and if they all agree, you can trust the fix. If they form a triangle (the **cocked hat**), you can see how big the error might be.",
                "**Which object to take first?** Here is the practical rule professional navigators use: **take the bearing of the object that is most abeam (broadside) first**. Why? Because abeam objects are changing their bearing the fastest as the ship moves. Taking them last means the bearing has changed from when you intended it. The objects dead ahead or dead astern are changing least — take them last.",
