                "The deviation card lists deviations for compass headings at fixed intervals (typically every 10 or 15 degrees). When the ship's heading falls between two tabulated headings, you must interpolate to find the exact deviation.",
                "## Simple Interpolation — Compass to Magnetic",
                "When converting from compass to magnetic (or true), you know the ship's head by compass, so you read the deviation directly from the card and interpolate if needed.",
                "**Example:** Deviation Card shows: 030 degrees (C) = 7 degrees W, and 040 degrees (C) = 9 degrees W. Find deviation for 035 degrees (C).\n1. Range of headings: 040 - 030 = 10 degrees.\n2. Required heading is 035, which is 5 degrees into the range (5/10 = 0.5 of the way).\n3. Range of deviations: 9 - 7 = 2 degrees.\n4. Interpolated deviation = 7 + (0.5 x 2) = 8 degrees W.",
                "## The Tricky Reverse — Magnetic to Compass (True to Compass)",
