                "**Tides** are the periodic rise and fall of sea level produced by the **gravitational attraction** of the Moon and Sun acting on the Earth's oceans. Tidal prediction is essential for passage planning in shallow waters, determining under-keel clearance, and timing bar crossings.",
                "## The Equilibrium Theory",
                "The Moon's gravity attracts water on the side of the Earth nearest to it, forming a **tidal bulge** on the near side. On the far side, the **centrifugal effect** of the Earth-Moon orbital system creates a second bulge. As the Earth rotates beneath these two bulges, any coastal location experiences **two high waters and two low waters** approximately every 24 hours 50 minutes (the **lunar day** — slightly longer than the solar day because the Moon is also orbiting).",
                "The Sun exerts a similar tidal force but only about **46% as strong** as the Moon's, despite the Sun's far greater mass — the tidal effect depends on the gradient of gravitational attraction, which decreases with distance cubed. Since the Sun is ~390 times further away than the Moon, its tidal effect is much smaller.",
                "## Spring Tides — Maximum Range",
                "When the Sun, Earth, and Moon are **approximately aligned** (a condition called **syzygy**), the tidal forces of the Sun and Moon act in the same direction and reinforce each other, producing **spring tides**. Spring tides occur at:",
