                "**Age of the Tide:** Spring tides do not occur exactly at new or full moon. Due to the inertia of the ocean's water mass, there is a delay of approximately 1 to 2 days between the astronomical alignment and the maximum tidal response. This delay is called the 'age of the tide'. At most ports, spring tides arrive about 36 to 48 hours after new or full moon.",
                "**Priming:** From full (or new) moon toward quarter moon, the time of high water occurs progressively earlier each day. The tide is said to be 'priming'. This happens because the Moon's tidal component and the Sun's tidal component are moving out of phase, and the combined peak shifts earlier.",
                "**Lagging:** From quarter moon toward new (or full) moon, high water occurs progressively later each day. The tide is said to be 'lagging'. The combined lunar and solar components are moving back into phase, and the combined peak shifts later.",
