                "**Chart Datum (CD)** is the reference level below which charted depths (soundings) are measured. In the UK and most countries worldwide, Chart Datum is set at **Lowest Astronomical Tide (LAT)** -- the lowest tide level predicted to occur under any combination of astronomical conditions (but excluding meteorological effects). This means charted depths are almost always conservative -- the actual water depth is equal to or greater than the charted depth.",
                "**Key Tidal Levels (from lowest to highest):**\n- **LAT** (Lowest Astronomical Tide) = Chart Datum (0.0 m on the chart)\n- **MLWS** (Mean Low Water Springs) -- average LW at spring tides\n- **MLWN** (Mean Low Water Neaps) -- average LW at neap tides\n- **MSL** (Mean Sea Level) -- the arithmetic mean of hourly heights over a long period (typically 19 years)\n- **MHWN** (Mean High Water Neaps) -- average HW at neap tides\n- **MHWS** (Mean High Water Springs) -- average HW at spring tides\n- **HAT** (Highest Astronomical Tide) -- the highest tide level predicted under any astronomical conditions",
                "**Drying Heights:** Features that are above Chart Datum but below MHWS are shown as drying heights on the chart (underlined in blue on Admiralty charts). Actual depth over a drying feature = Height of tide - Drying height. If this value is negative, the feature is exposed (dry).",
                "**Bridge and Cable Clearances:** Vertical clearances on charts are measured above **MHWS** (or HAT in some countries). So at MHWS, you get exactly the charted clearance. At lower tides, you get MORE clearance. At exceptional tides above MHWS (storm surge), you get LESS clearance. Air Draft = Height from waterline to highest fixed point on vessel. The vessel can pass under a bridge if: (Bridge height above CD) - (Height of tide) > Air Draft + safety margin.",
                "**Height of Tide:** The vertical distance of the actual water surface above Chart Datum at any given moment. Actual depth at any point = Charted depth + Height of tide. If the height of tide is negative (extremely rare -- actual level below LAT), actual depth is less than charted depth."
