                "**Semi-diurnal Tides:** Two high waters and two low waters of approximately equal height each lunar day (~24h 50min). This is the most common pattern worldwide, found along the coasts of the UK, most of Europe, the east coast of Africa, and the Indian subcontinent. The tidal curve approximates a sinusoidal shape, making the Rule of Twelfths a reasonable approximation.",
                "**Diurnal Tides:** Only one high water and one low water per day. Found in the Gulf of Mexico, parts of Southeast Asia, and some Pacific islands. The tidal period is approximately 24 hours 50 minutes for the complete cycle.",
                "**Mixed Tides:** Two high waters and two low waters per day, but with significant inequality -- one HW is notably higher than the other, and/or one LW is notably lower. Found on the US West Coast, parts of the Indian Ocean, and Australian coasts. The Admiralty Tide Tables for such ports show four daily entries: MHHW (Mean Higher High Water), MLHW (Mean Lower High Water), MHLW (Mean Higher Low Water), and MLLW (Mean Lower Low Water).",
                "**Diurnal Inequality:** When the Moon has significant declination (north or south of the equator), the two tidal bulges are tilted relative to the equator. An observer rotating through these tilted bulges experiences one larger and one smaller tide per day. Diurnal inequality is greatest when the Moon's declination is at maximum (near the solstices -- these are called 'solsticial tides'). When the Moon is over the equator (near equinoxes), the two daily tides are most nearly equal."
