                "**Barometric Pressure:** A fall of 1 millibar below the mean value causes the sea level to rise by approximately 1 cm (the 'inverted barometer effect'). A deep depression (e.g., 970 mb vs. standard 1013 mb) can raise the water level by about 0.4 m.",
                "**Wind Effect:** Strong persistent onshore winds pile water against the coast, raising levels. Strong offshore winds push water away, lowering levels. In shallow coastal areas like the North Sea, wind effects can be very significant -- adding or subtracting 1-2 metres from the predicted tide.",
