              title: "COLREGS — All Rules Overview",
              body: "The International Regulations for Preventing Collisions at Sea (COLREGS 1972) are mandatory international law under SOLAS. They apply to all vessels on the high seas and connected navigable waters.\n\nStructure: Part A (Rules 1–3) — Definitions. Part B (Rules 4–19) — Steering and Sailing: Section I all conditions, Section II vessels in sight, Section III restricted visibility. Part C (Rules 20–31) — Lights and Shapes. Part D (Rules 32–37) — Sound and Light Signals.\n\nKey Rules: Rule 5 (Look-out — all available means, always). Rule 6 (Safe speed — can stop in time). Rule 7 (Risk of collision — if in doubt, it exists; constant bearing = risk). Rule 8 (Action — large, early, positive). Rule 16 (Give-way vessel — keep well clear). Rule 17 (Stand-on vessel — maintain course and speed; action permitted if collision inevitable). Rule 18 Hierarchy: NUC > RAM > CBD > Fishing > Sailing > Power-driven. Rule 19 (Restricted visibility — no vessels in sight: alter to starboard, avoid altering to port, do not cross ahead)."
