              body: "A vessel is in an overtaking situation when she is approaching another vessel from a direction more than 22.5° abaft the other vessel's beam — in other words, she is approaching from within the sternlight sector (135° arc centred on dead astern). The practical test: if at night you can see only the sternlight of the vessel ahead (no sidelights), you are overtaking. If you can see a sidelight, you are in a crossing situation. Once established as overtaking, the overtaking vessel must keep clear until she is finally past and clear — the overtaking rule applies even if the vessels' types would normally give the overtaking vessel priority under Rule 18. Compass bearing test: if the bearing of the overtaken vessel does not change but you are gaining on her, it is NOT a risk-of-collision crossing situation — it is overtaking."
