              body: "GPS (Global Positioning System) consists of three segments: Space (31 satellites at ~20,200km), Control (ground stations), User (receivers). A 3D fix requires 4 satellites (3 for position + 1 for receiver clock error). Accuracy: civilian ±3–10m; DGPS ±1–3m. Errors: ionospheric delay, multipath, satellite geometry (HDOP). HDOP < 2 = excellent. GPS vulnerabilities: jamming, spoofing, solar interference — always cross-check with radar or visual fix.\n\nAIS (Automatic Identification System) uses VHF Ch 87B/88B. Class A mandatory for ships ≥300 GT on international voyages; updates every 2s (manoeuvring) to 3 min (at anchor). Transmits: static data (MMSI, name, type, dimensions), dynamic data (position, COG, SOG, heading, ROT, nav status), voyage data (draught, destination, ETA). AIS limitations: vessels with no AIS; incorrect manual entries; spoofing possible. AIS is NOT a collision avoidance tool — does not replace radar or visual lookout.\n\nEPIRB: 406 MHz to COSPAS-SARSAT satellites; internal GPS gives position ±100m; must be registered with national authority. Radar SART: 9GHz (X-band); shows 12 dots on radar. NAVTEX: 518 kHz; navigational warnings and weather. DSC: VHF Ch 70; keep continuous watch. AIS-SART: shows as AIS target on ECDIS."
