                "- A terrestrial bearing taken simultaneously or at a later time",
                "- A second celestial observation of a different body (or the same body at a different time)",
                "## Running Fix: Astro PL + Terrestrial Bearing",
                "Step 1: At the time of the celestial observation, plot the position through which the PL passes (either the Lon-by-Chron position or the ITP from the intercept method). Draw the PL perpendicular to the azimuth.",
                "Step 2: From the point on the PL, lay off the true course steered and the distance run during the interval between the celestial observation and the terrestrial bearing.",
                "Step 3: Through the new point, draw the transferred position line (TPL) parallel to the original PL.",
                "Step 4: Draw the true bearing of the terrestrial object taken at the second time.",
                "Step 5: Where the TPL cuts the terrestrial bearing is the ship's position at the time of the terrestrial bearing.",
                "## Running Fix: Astro PL + Astro PL (e.g., AM Sun + Noon Sun)",
                "In practice, a morning observation of the Sun gives a PL. The ship continues on course until the Sun is at or near the meridian (local noon). A second observation gives a second PL (at noon, the Sun bears due North or South, so the PL runs East-West — a parallel of latitude). Transfer the morning PL forward by course and distance run, and cross it with the noon PL for the fix.",
