              body: "The sextant reading (hs) is not directly usable in the PZX triangle. Three corrections must be applied in order to produce the True Observed Altitude (Ho).\n\nStep 1 — Index Error (IE): The sextant's own zero error. If IE is ON the arc (sextant reads positive when set to zero): subtract. If OFF the arc (reads negative): add. Mnemonic: 'If it's on, take it off; if it's off, put it on.'\n\nStep 2 — Dip: Your eye is above sea level, so the visible horizon dips below the true horizon. Dip is ALWAYS negative (subtracted). Dip = −1.77' × √(height of eye in metres). After IE and Dip: Apparent Altitude (ha).\n\nStep 3 — Main Correction: From the Nautical Almanac. Combines refraction (always negative, large near the horizon), semi-diameter (Sun/Moon: +SD for lower limb, −SD for upper limb), and parallax (significant only for Moon). After main correction: True Altitude (Ho)."
