              title: "Compass Error by Amplitude and Azimuth",
              body: "Compass error (CE) is the total angular difference between Compass North and True North: CE = Variation + Deviation. Regular compass error checks are required by SOLAS and good seamanship — at least once per watch.\n\nAmplitude method: used at the exact moment of sunrise or sunset (body on the rational horizon, altitude = 0°). Formula: sin(Amplitude) = sin(Dec) ÷ cos(Lat). The result is named E (rising) or W (setting), then N/S same as declination. Convert to true bearing: E-N → 090° − A; E-S → 090° + A; W-N → 270° + A; W-S → 270° − A. CE = True Bearing − Compass Bearing.\n\nAzimuth method: can be used at any time. Calculate LHA from GHA and longitude, then use ABC Tables (Norie's) to find true azimuth Zn. CE = Zn − Compass Bearing. Deviation = CE − Variation."
