          { id: "t-met-3-pq", name: "Solved Past Question Papers", content: "",
            sections: [
              { type: "callout", kind: "exam-tip", title: "📝 About This Section", body: "You must identify all 10 cloud genera by name, type (high/medium/low), and associated weather. Cloud identification is tested in both written and oral examinations." },
              { type: "narrative", title: "Q. (MMD Dec 2020, Jan 2020) Describe the different types of clouds giving the probable height of formation of each type.", paragraphs: [
                "Clouds are classified by the WMO into 10 genera based on height and form:",
                "HIGH CLOUDS (above 6 km / 20,000 ft — composed of ice crystals): (1) Cirrus (Ci) — thin, wispy, fibrous, white. Often called 'mare's tails'. (2) Cirrostratus (Cs) — thin whitish veil covering the sky. Produces halos around sun/moon. (3) Cirrocumulus (Cc) — small white puffs/ripples in rows. 'Mackerel sky'.",
                "MEDIUM CLOUDS (2–6 km / 6,500–20,000 ft — water droplets, sometimes ice): (4) Altostratus (As) — grey/blue sheet. Sun visible 'as through frosted glass'. Often precedes frontal rain. (5) Altocumulus (Ac) — white/grey patches or rolls. Castellanus type indicates instability.",
                "LOW CLOUDS (below 2 km / 6,500 ft — water droplets): (6) Stratus (St) — grey, uniform layer. May produce drizzle. Fog is stratus at ground level. (7) Stratocumulus (Sc) — grey/white lumpy rolls or patches. Most common cloud type. (8) Nimbostratus (Ns) — thick, dark grey, featureless. Produces continuous moderate to heavy rain.",
                "CLOUDS OF VERTICAL DEVELOPMENT (base low, tops may reach 15+ km): (9) Cumulus (Cu) — white, puffy, flat base. Fair weather (humilis) or growing (congestus). (10) Cumulonimbus (Cb) — towering with anvil top. Produces heavy rain, thunder, lightning, hail, squalls, waterspouts. Most dangerous cloud for mariners."
              ]},
              { type: "narrative", title: "Q. (MMD Mar 2020, Jan 2020) Explain how convection and orographic clouds are formed.", paragraphs: [
                "CONVECTION CLOUDS: (1) The sun heats the ground, which heats the air above it. (2) Warm air rises as thermals (convection currents). (3) As it rises, it cools adiabatically at the DALR (10°C/km). (4) When it reaches the dew point, water vapour condenses — a cloud forms. (5) The cloud base is the condensation level. (6) If the air is unstable, the cloud keeps growing: Cu humilis → Cu congestus → Cb. (7) Common over land in the afternoon (maximum heating) and over warm ocean currents.",
                "OROGRAPHIC CLOUDS: (1) Wind blows moist air toward a mountain or hill. (2) Air is forced to rise over the obstacle (orographic lifting). (3) As it rises, it cools adiabatically. (4) At the dew point, cloud forms on the windward slope. (5) Rain falls on the windward side (orographic rainfall). (6) On the lee side, the now-drier air descends and warms — clear conditions (rain shadow). (7) Lenticular (lens-shaped) clouds may form in standing waves on the lee side. (8) Examples: persistent cloud caps on mountain peaks, Western Ghats monsoon rainfall."
              ]}
            ],
            mcqs: [
              { q: "The three levels of cloud classification are:", options: ["A) High, medium, low", "B) Thin, medium, thick", "C) Fast, slow, stationary", "D) Warm, cold, neutral"], correct: 0, explanation: "Clouds are classified by height: High (above 6,000 m): Cirrus, Cirrostratus, Cirrocumulus. Medium (2,000-6,000 m): Altostratus, Altocumulus. Low (below 2,000 m): Stratus, Stratocumulus, Nimbostratus. Cumulonimbus and Cumulus extend through multiple levels." },
              { q: "Cumulonimbus clouds are associated with:", options: ["A) Fine settled weather", "B) Heavy rain, thunderstorms, hail, squalls, and possible tornadoes", "C) Light drizzle only", "D) Clear skies"], correct: 1, explanation: "Cumulonimbus (Cb) is the most active cloud type — towering from near the surface to the tropopause. It produces heavy rain, thunderstorms, lightning, hail, squalls, strong gusts, and occasionally tornadoes or waterspouts. The anvil-shaped top is characteristic." },
              { q: "Cirrus clouds are composed of:", options: ["A) Water droplets", "B) Ice crystals", "C) A mixture of water and ice", "D) Dust particles"], correct: 1, explanation: "Cirrus (Ci) forms at high altitudes (above 6,000 m) where temperatures are well below freezing. They are composed entirely of ice crystals, giving them their characteristic wispy, fibrous, or hair-like appearance (mare's tails)." },
              { q: "A halo around the Sun or Moon indicates:", options: ["A) Fog is forming", "B) Cirrostratus cloud (ice crystals) — often a precursor to an approaching warm front", "C) Fine weather for the next 24 hours", "D) A cold front has passed"], correct: 1, explanation: "Haloes are formed by refraction of light through ice crystals in Cirrostratus (Cs) cloud. Cirrostratus often precedes a warm front by 12-24 hours. 'Halo around the moon, rain is coming soon' has some meteorological basis." },
              { q: "Nimbostratus produces:", options: ["A) No precipitation", "B) Continuous steady rain or snow (not showery)", "C) Thunderstorms only", "D) Hail only"], correct: 1, explanation: "Nimbostratus (Ns) is a thick, grey, featureless cloud layer that produces continuous moderate to heavy rain or snow. It is associated with warm fronts and occluded fronts. Visibility below Ns is often poor." },
              { q: "Fog is essentially:", options: ["A) A type of rain", "B) Cloud at ground level (stratus with base at the surface)", "C) Smoke", "D) Haze"], correct: 1, explanation: "Fog is defined as visibility reduced below 1,000 m by water droplets suspended in the air. It is essentially stratus cloud with its base at or very near the surface. When visibility is 1,000-5,000 m, it is classified as mist." },
              { q: "Altocumulus castellanus clouds indicate:", options: ["A) Stable conditions", "B) Instability at mid-levels — potential for thunderstorm development", "C) Clearing weather", "D) Fog formation"], correct: 1, explanation: "Altocumulus castellanus (turret-like towers rising from a common base) indicates instability at mid-levels. If seen in the morning, thunderstorms may develop by afternoon. They are an important indicator of potential severe weather." },
              { q: "The cloud associated with a passing warm front (in order) is:", options: ["A) Cb → Ns → As → Cs → Ci (back to front)", "B) Ci → Cs → As → Ns (high clouds first, then progressively lower)", "C) St → Cu → Cb", "D) Fog → Stratus → Clear sky"], correct: 1, explanation: "Approaching warm front: first high Cirrus (Ci), then Cirrostratus (Cs — haloes), then Altostratus (As — watery sun), then Nimbostratus (Ns — continuous rain). After the front passes: warm sector with low Stratus/Stratocumulus and possible drizzle." },
              { q: "Cumulus clouds form by:", options: ["A) Orographic lifting only", "B) Convection — warm air rising from the heated surface", "C) Frontal activity only", "D) Radiation cooling"], correct: 1, explanation: "Cumulus clouds form primarily by convection — the Sun heats the ground, warm air rises (thermals), cools adiabatically, and condenses when it reaches the dew point. Fair-weather cumulus (Cu humilis) has limited vertical extent. Cumulus congestus grows taller and may develop into Cumulonimbus." },
              { q: "Stratocumulus is the most common cloud type and is characterised by:", options: ["A) Towering vertical development", "B) A lumpy, rolling layer of grey/white cloud, often covering most of the sky", "C) A thin wispy appearance", "D) Continuous heavy rain"], correct: 1, explanation: "Stratocumulus (Sc) is the most common cloud type globally. It appears as a layer of rounded masses or rolls of grey/white cloud. It may produce light drizzle but often no precipitation. It is typical of maritime polar air masses and trade wind inversions." },
              { q: "Cumulonimbus (Cb) clouds are associated with:", options: ["A) Heavy rain, thunderstorms, hail, lightning, turbulence, and wind squalls", "B) Fine weather only", "C) Fog", "D) Drizzle only"], correct: 0, explanation: "Cb is the most significant weather cloud. It develops vertically through all three cloud levels, producing heavy precipitation (rain, hail), thunderstorms, lightning, severe turbulence, strong updrafts/downdrafts, and can spawn waterspouts or tornadoes." },
              { q: "The typical cloud sequence as a warm front approaches is:", options: ["A) Cirrus \u2192 Cirrostratus \u2192 Altostratus \u2192 Nimbostratus (high to low)", "B) Cumulus \u2192 Stratus \u2192 Fog", "C) Clear sky \u2192 Fog \u2192 Rain", "D) Stratocumulus \u2192 Cirrus \u2192 Clear"], correct: 0, explanation: "A warm front has a gentle slope. The first signs are high cirrus, then cirrostratus (halo), then progressively lower altostratus (watery sun), and finally nimbostratus with continuous rain. This sequence may take 12-24 hours as the front approaches." },
              { q: "Lenticular clouds indicate:", options: ["A) Strong winds aloft with wave motion \u2014 standing waves forming downwind of mountains", "B) Fair weather", "C) Approaching cold front", "D) Calm conditions"], correct: 0, explanation: "Lenticular (lens-shaped) clouds form in standing (stationary) waves on the lee side of mountains when stable air is forced over the terrain. They indicate strong winds at that altitude and can be a sign of turbulence for aviation and severe conditions at sea near mountainous coasts." },
              { q: "Fog is classified as a cloud type:", options: ["A) Stratus at ground level \u2014 visibility less than 1 km", "B) A type of cumulus", "C) A type of cirrus", "D) Not considered a cloud"], correct: 0, explanation: "Fog is stratus cloud with its base at or very near the ground surface, reducing visibility below 1 km (by definition). If visibility is 1-5 km with similar conditions, it is called mist." },
              { q: "Cirrus clouds are composed of:", options: ["A) Ice crystals at heights above 6 km", "B) Water droplets at low levels", "C) Dust particles", "D) A mixture of ice and water at middle levels"], correct: 0, explanation: "Cirrus (Ci) clouds form at high altitudes (above 6 km / 20,000 ft) where temperatures are well below freezing. They are composed entirely of ice crystals and appear as thin, wispy, white filaments or patches." }
]
          }
