              { q: "After a cold front passes, what changes occur in wind, temperature, and pressure?", options: ["A) Wind veers, temperature rises, pressure falls", "B) Wind backs, temperature falls, pressure falls", "C) Wind veers, temperature falls sharply, pressure rises", "D) Wind backs, temperature rises, pressure rises"], answer: 2, explanation: "After cold front passage in NH: wind VEERS (backs in SH), temperature drops sharply (cold air behind), pressure RISES, visibility improves markedly, showery weather with Cb/Cu." },
              { q: "What type of front forms when a cold front overtakes a warm front?", options: ["A) Stationary front", "B) Occluded front", "C) Quasi-stationary front", "D) Retreating front"], answer: 1, explanation: "When the cold front (moving faster) catches up with the warm front, the warm sector is lifted completely off the surface — this is called an Occlusion or Occluded Front. Cold-type occlusion: colder air behind cold front. Warm-type occlusion: less cold air behind." }
