              { q: "Under COLREGS, when must a vessel proceed at a 'safe speed' in fog?", options: ["A) Only at night", "B) Whenever visibility is restricted, at all times", "C) Only when anchored vessels are heard", "D) Only in TSS areas"], answer: 1, explanation: "COLREGS Rule 19 and Rule 6: In any condition of restricted visibility a vessel must proceed at a SAFE SPEED — defined as a speed that allows the vessel to take proper and effective action to avoid collision and stop within an appropriate distance. This applies at ALL times in restricted visibility." },
              { q: "What is 'steam fog' or 'Arctic sea smoke' and when does it form?", options: ["A) Fog from industrial smoke mixing with sea spray", "B) Fog formed when cold dry air moves over warm sea — water vapour condenses immediately above surface", "C) Fog caused by heavy rain evaporating before reaching ground", "D) Fog formed at a warm front"], answer: 1, explanation: "Steam fog (Arctic sea smoke) forms when very cold, dry polar air flows over relatively warm open water. Water evaporates rapidly and immediately condenses in the cold air above the surface, creating dramatic rising wisps of 'steam'." }
