            name: "Charter Parties & Bills of Lading",
            content: `**Charter Parties**

A charter party is a contract between a shipowner and a charterer for the hire of a vessel or cargo space.

**Types of Charter Party**

1. **Voyage Charter**
   - Ship hired for a specific voyage (port A to port B) to carry a specific cargo
   - Freight is paid per unit of cargo (per tonne, per m³) or as a lump sum
   - Owner pays for vessel expenses (fuel, crew, maintenance); charterer pays port costs (unless stated otherwise)
   - Charterer has a fixed time (laytime) to load and discharge; if exceeded, demurrage is payable
   - Common forms: GENCON (general cargo), ASBATANKVOY (tankers), NORGRAIN (grain)

2. **Time Charter**
   - Ship hired for a period of time (e.g. 6 months, 1 year)
   - Owner pays for crew, maintenance, insurance; charterer pays fuel (bunkers) and port charges
   - Charterer directs the commercial operation (routes, cargoes, ports) within contractual limits
   - Hire paid at regular intervals (e.g. every 15 days); if hire not paid, owner may withdraw the ship
   - Common forms: NYPE (New York Produce Exchange), BALTIME

3. **Bareboat (Demise) Charter**
   - Charterer takes over full possession and control of the ship — including crew, management, insurance
   - Charterer effectively becomes the owner for the charter period
   - Used for long-term arrangements; charterer responsible for all costs
   - May lead to flag change and re-registration

**Key Charter Party Terms**
- **Laytime**: contractually agreed time allowed for loading/discharging
- **Demurrage**: compensation payable by charterer to owner if laytime is exceeded (detention of ship)
- **Despatch**: payment by owner to charterer if loading/discharging is completed ahead of laytime (reward for efficiency)
- **NOR (Notice of Readiness)**: formal notice given by master to charterer/agent that ship has arrived, is ready, and laytime is about to commence
- **WIBON/WIPON/WICCON**: "Whether in berth or not / Whether in port or not / Whether in customs clearance or not" — determines when laytime starts
- **Safe port warranty**: charterer warrants that nominated ports are safe

**Bill of Lading (B/L)**

A bill of lading is a document issued by the carrier (or master on behalf of the carrier) to the shipper. It serves three functions:

1. **Receipt for goods**: evidence that the cargo was received by the carrier in apparent good order and condition
2. **Evidence of contract of carriage**: contains or evidences the terms of the contract
3. **Document of title**: endorsement and delivery of the B/L transfers title (ownership) of the cargo — it is a negotiable instrument

**Types of B/L**
- **Clean B/L**: no reservations about condition or quantity of cargo
- **Claused/Dirty B/L**: contains notations indicating cargo damage, shortage, or defective packaging
- **Shipped B/L**: certifies cargo has been placed on board the named vessel
- **Received for Shipment B/L**: certifies cargo received by carrier but not yet necessarily loaded
- **Straight B/L**: non-negotiable, consigned to a specific named party
- **Order B/L**: negotiable, consigned "to order" — can be endorsed to another party
- **Sea Waybill**: non-negotiable; no document of title but used where quick delivery is needed

**Hague-Visby Rules**
The Hague-Visby Rules govern the carrier's liability:
- Package limitation: SDR 666.67 per package or SDR 2 per kg, whichever is higher
- Carrier must exercise due diligence to make the ship seaworthy before and at the beginning of the voyage
- 17 carrier defences include: navigation error, fire (unless carrier's fault), act of God, act of war, inherent vice

**Role of the Master**
- May be authorised to sign B/Ls on behalf of the owner/carrier
- Should not sign a B/L for cargo not actually loaded, or sign a clean B/L for damaged cargo (fraudulent)
- A letter of indemnity (LOI) asking the master to sign a clean B/L for damaged cargo is generally not valid protection`,
