            name: "STCW Convention & Manning",
            content: `**STCW Convention (Standards of Training, Certification and Watchkeeping for Seafarers)**

The STCW Convention (1978, as amended — particularly the 1995 and 2010 Manila Amendments) sets minimum qualification standards for masters, officers, and watch personnel on seagoing merchant ships.

**Structure**
- **Convention**: the legal framework agreed by states
- **STCW Code Part A**: mandatory minimum standards (training, competency tables)
- **STCW Code Part B**: recommended guidance

**Manila Amendments (2010) — Key Changes**
- Updated competency standards (new chapters for ECDIS, BRM, leadership)
- New requirements for security training (ISPS-related)
- Strengthened medical standards
- New requirements for tanker training
- Mandatory rest hours strengthened
- Measures to prevent fraudulent certificates

**Certificates Required — Officer of the Watch (OOW) — Deck**
- STCW II/1: OOW Certificate (500+ GT international service)
- Prerequisites: approved seagoing service, approved training, GMDSS, medical fitness
- Revalidation: every 5 years — demonstrate continued professional competency or approved sea service

**Chief Mate and Master**
- STCW II/2: Certificate of Competency as Master/Chief Mate (3000+ GT)
- STCW II/3: Master/OOW on ships of less than 500 GT

**Watchkeeping Hours — STCW Regulation VIII/1**
- Minimum rest: 10 hours in any 24-hour period; 77 hours in any 7-day period
- Rest may be split into no more than 2 periods, one of which is at least 6 hours
- Exceptions in emergencies at master's discretion (but records must reflect actual rest)

**Safe Manning**
- Every ship must have a Minimum Safe Manning Document (MSMD) issued by the flag state
- Based on: ship type, size, area of operation, machinery, watch system
- Manning below the MSMD is a deficiency — grounds for PSC detention

**Basic Safety Training (BST) — STCW VI/1**
All seafarers must hold certificates in:
- Personal Survival Techniques
- Fire Prevention and Fire Fighting
- Elementary First Aid
- Personal Safety and Social Responsibilities

**Proficiency Certificates (Endorsements)**
- Advanced Fire Fighting (STCW VI/3) — required for officers
- Medical First Aid, Medical Care
- Survival Craft and Rescue Boats (STCW VI/2) — lifeboat coxswain
- Fast Rescue Boat
- ECDIS type-specific training (mandatory since 2012)
- Tanker endorsements: Basic/Advanced tanker training (oil, chemical, gas)

**Maritime Labour Convention (MLC 2006)**
- "Seafarers' Bill of Rights"
- Standards for: minimum age (16 years, watchkeeping 18 years), employment agreements (SEA), wages, hours of work/rest, repatriation, accommodation, food, health care, social security
- Maritime Labour Certificate (MLC): issued to ships ≥500 GT in international service; valid 5 years with intermediate inspection
- Declaration of Maritime Labour Compliance (DMLC): two parts — (1) flag state standards, (2) company's implementation measures

**Port State Control (PSC)**
PSC officers can inspect any foreign ship in port to verify compliance with SOLAS, MARPOL, STCW, MLC, COLREGS, Load Line conventions. Deficiencies may lead to detention.`,
