            name: "Life-Saving Appliances (LSA)",
            content: `**Life-Saving Appliances — SOLAS Chapter III & LSA Code**

The LSA Code (Resolution MSC.48(66)) provides specific design and performance standards for all life-saving appliances required under SOLAS Chapter III.

**Survival Craft — Lifeboats**

*Totally Enclosed Motor Lifeboats (TEMB)*
- Required on most cargo ships (SOLAS III/31)
- Must be capable of being launched and recovered with all occupants
- Self-contained air supply (10 minutes minimum)
- Buoyancy material attached (cannot sink if flooded)
- Engine must start within 2 minutes at −15°C to +65°C
- Propulsion: min speed 6 knots in calm water with full complement
- Free-fall lifeboat: deployed by falling directly into the sea; used on bulk carriers/tankers

*Rescue Boats*
- Must be carried on every ship
- Minimum speed: 6 knots for 4 hours with full complement
- Must be able to recover persons from water

**Liferaft**
- Inflatable liferafts (ILR): packed in GRP containers; inflate automatically when painter line is pulled
- Hydrostatic release unit (HRU): automatically releases liferaft when ship sinks to 1.5–4 m depth
- Weak link: breaks under force, allowing inflated raft to float free
- Annual servicing at approved station; max 30 months between services

**Lifebuoys**
- At least one each side with self-igniting light and buoyant lifeline (≥30 m)
- At least two with self-activating smoke signal
- Self-igniting light duration: ≥2 hours

**Immersion Suits & Thermal Protective Aids (TPA)**
- Immersion suit: core temperature maintained for at least 6 hours in water 0–2°C
- Must be donned in ≤2 minutes (including lifejacket)

**Lifejackets**
- Sufficient for all on board + 10% extra at assembly stations
- Lifejacket light: duration ≥8 hours
- SOLAS performance: turn an unconscious person face-up within 5 seconds

**EPIRBs (Emergency Position-Indicating Radio Beacons)**
- 406 MHz COSPAS-SARSAT EPIRBs transmit to satellite system
- Class I (float-free, auto-activating): releases and activates automatically when ship sinks
- Class II (manual activation): manually activated; taken into survival craft
- Battery life: ≥48 hours; hydrostatic release activation at 1–4 m

**SART (Search and Rescue Transponder)**
- Responds to X-band radar (9 GHz) with a row of dots on the radar screen
- Range: up to 10 nm (aircraft), ~5 nm (ship's radar)
- Two per ship (SOLAS); one in each survival craft

**AIS-SART**
- Transmits AIS signal (position) when activated; shown as a target on AIS display

**Drills and Training**
- Abandon ship drill: within 24 hours of departure if >25% crew changed; monthly (SOLAS III/19)
- Fire drill: same schedule; alternated with abandon ship drill so both conducted monthly
- Lifeboat drill: every 3 months, lifeboat to be lowered to water and manoeuvred`,
